let obj = {
    name: "shekar",
    age: 23,
    greet(){
      return `hello ${this.name}`;
    }
}

const a = obj.greet.bind(obj);
console.log(a());
You get hello undefined because the function loses its connection to the obj object when you assign it to a new variable.
## Why This Happens

* The this keyword is dynamic: In JavaScript, this is not determined by where a function is defined, but by how it is called.
* Method invocation: When you call obj.greet(), JavaScript sees obj before the dot, so this points to obj.
* Function invocation: When you assign obj.greet to the variable a, you are extracting the bare function. When you call a(), it is executed as a regular function.
* The fallback: In regular function calls, this defaults to the global window object (or undefined in strict mode). Since window.name is not defined, this.name returns undefined.

## How to Fix It
You can fix this using three common methods:
## 1. Use bind() to lock this
The bind() method explicitly couples the function to a specific object, no matter how it is called.

const a = obj.greet.bind(obj);
console.log(a()); // Output: hello shekar

## 2. Call it directly
Avoid assigning the method to a variable if you do not need to.

console.log(obj.greet()); // Output: hello shekar

## 3. Use an arrow function in the object
Arrow functions do not have their own this. They inherit this from the surrounding scope where the object was created.

let obj = {
    name: "shekar",
    age: 23,
    greet: () => `hello ${obj.name}` // Direct reference to obj
}

