Yes, creating multiple objects with the same method is a very common requirement in JavaScript development. If you need to make many objects (like users, products, or players) that share the same behavior, copying and pasting the method inside every single object is inefficient and uses too much memory. [1, 2, 3, 4, 5] 
Here are the three best ways to handle this, ranked from modern to traditional:
## 1. Use JavaScript Classes (Recommended) [6] 
Classes act as a blueprint. The method is defined once on the prototype, so every new object shares the exact same function in memory, and this automatically points to the specific object you call it on. [7, 8, 9, 10] 

class Person {
    constructor(name, age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }

    greet() {
        return `hello ${this.name}`;
    }
}
const user1 = new Person("shekar", 23);const user2 = new Person("rahul", 25);

console.log(user1.greet()); // Output: hello shekar
console.log(user2.greet()); // Output: hello rahul

## 2. Use a Constructor Function [11] 
This is the older ES5 way of doing what classes do. It achieves the exact same performance benefit by attaching the method to the function's prototype. [12] 

function Person(name, age) {
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
}

Person.prototype.greet = function() {
    return `hello ${this.name}`;
};
const user1 = new Person("shekar", 23);
console.log(user1.greet()); // Output: hello shekar

## 3. Use a Factory Function [13] 
If you want to avoid the new keyword and the confusing this behavior entirely, a factory function creates and returns a new object. To fix the undefined issue from your first question, you can pre-bind the method before returning it. [14] 

function createPerson(name, age) {
    const obj = {
        name: name,
        age: age,
        greet() {
            return `hello ${this.name}`;
        }
    };
    
    // Automatically binds the method so it never loses context
    obj.greet = obj.greet.bind(obj); 
    return obj;
}
const user1 = createPerson("shekar", 23);const a = user1.greet; 
console.log(a()); // Output: hello shekar (Works perfectly!)

